{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"374"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471545"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"374"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/374"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.71,0.1,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87005"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71262"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1044"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43795"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87005"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 11-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent, who is concerned about his height. Both parents are tall with a mid-parental height of 185 cm (95th percentile). He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His father has hypertension, and his mother has type 1 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His height is on the third percentile and weight on the 10th percentile. There is a small ulcer in the left buccal mucosa. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe reports a lack of appetite, occasional abdominal pain, and a sore mouth. He feels he has lost weight but has not weighed himself. He opens his bowels four times per day and often has to rush to the bathroom between classes. He denies blood or mucus in the stool. He denies dyspnoea, urinary changes, nausea, vomiting, abdominal bloating, skin rashes or headaches. His only exercise is walking to school daily. He feels anxious about his height and has difficulty sleeping.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duodenal biopsy","Anti-endomysial and transglutaminase antibodies","Thyroid stimulating hormone and free thyroxine","CT abdomen","Stool microscopy, culture and sensitivity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy presents with symptoms suggestive of either inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) or coeliac disease. The most appropriate initial investigation is \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-endomysial and transglutaminase antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E, which are serological markers for coeliac disease. This non-invasive test is preferable before subjecting an 11-year-old to more invasive procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe child\u0027s poor growth (height on third percentile) despite having tall parents suggests pathology rather than genetic short stature. Mid-parental height is calculated by adding the parents\u0027 heights and dividing by two, then adding 6.5 cm for boys or subtracting 6.5 cm for girls. A child\u0027s height typically falls within 8.5 cm of their mid-parental height, making this child\u0027s height particularly concerning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECoeliac disease is an immune-mediated enteropathy triggered by gluten exposure in genetically susceptible individuals. Growth failure is a common presentation in children, occurring due to malabsorption of nutrients, particularly iron, folate, vitamin D, and zinc. The inflammatory process in the small intestine leads to villous atrophy, reducing the surface area available for nutrient absorption. This, combined with chronic diarrhoea, anorexia, and abdominal pain, strongly suggests malabsorption. Coeliac disease should be ruled out first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eduodenal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed the gold standard for diagnosing both coeliac disease and IBD. However, it is an invasive procedure requiring anaesthesia and should not be the first-line investigation in this case. It would be considered if the serology is positive or if symptoms persist despite negative serology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone and free thyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E tests are used to diagnose thyroid disorders. While hyperthyroidism could explain some symptoms like anxiety and increased bowel movements, it wouldn\u0027t account for the growth concerns and oral ulcers. Therefore, it\u0027s not the most appropriate initial test in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a first-line investigation for suspected IBD or coeliac disease in children due to radiation exposure. It may be considered later in the diagnostic process if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStool microscopy, culture and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E are useful for identifying infectious causes of diarrhoea. While important in the overall workup, they are not the most appropriate initial test given the chronic nature of this boy\u0027s symptoms and his growth concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter coeliac serology, further investigations may include inflammatory markers (ESR, CRP), faecal calprotectin, and eventually endoscopy with biopsies if IBD is still suspected. The key is to start with non-invasive tests and progress to more invasive investigations as needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-invasive diagnostic investigations should take priority in the initial assessment of suspected coeliac disease or inflammatory bowel disease in children.","Coeliac serology (anti-endomysial and transglutaminase antibodies) is the most appropriate initial investigation for a child presenting with chronic diarrhoea, abdominal pain, and growth concerns.","The clinical presentation of coeliac disease can overlap with inflammatory bowel disease, necessitating careful diagnostic workup.","Poor growth in a child with tall parents suggests pathology rather than genetic short stature."],"references":["Higuchi LM, Bousvaros, A. Clinical presentation and diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease in children. In: Heyman MB, Hppin AG. UpToDate [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2021 [2021 Feb; cited 2021 Mar 07]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-presentation-and-diagnosis-of-inflammatory-bowel-disease-in-children","Ivor DH. Epidemiology, pathogenesis, and clinical manifestations of celiac disease in children. In: Li BU, Hoppin AG. UpToDate [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2021 [2021 Feb; cited 2021 Feb 07]. Available from:\u00a0 https://www.uptodate.com/contents/epidemiology-pathogenesis-and-clinical-manifestations-of-celiac-disease-in-children"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71262"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"374"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71262"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-25T13:13:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-25T13:14:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"374"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87005"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"a